#open-question(title: [Multi-Organ Epigenetic Aging in ME/CFS])[
Do ME/CFS patients show heterochronous epigenetic aging (large variance across tissue-specific aging clocks), and does sleep-timing synchronization reduce this variance?

*Rationale*: Wen et al. (2026) show multi-organ aging effects of sleep duration @MULTIConsortium2026SleepChartBiologicalAging. ME/CFS may have heterochronous aging across brain, heart, lung, and immune clocks.

*Measurement*: Tissue-specific epigenetic clocks from blood, saliva, and possibly other accessible tissues. Compare variance across clock types in ME/CFS vs. controls. Correlate with sleep timing and circadian phase markers.

*Evidence gap*: No ME/CFS-specific data on multi-organ aging clocks or sleep-circadian synchronization effects.
] <oq:multi-organ-epigenetic-aging>
